bout 1168":"okolo 1123–okolo 1168","1131–1187":"1131–1187","1157–1187":"1157–1187","1123–1168":"1123–1168","1168":"1168","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","about 1123":"okolo 1123","about 1157":"okolo 1157","about 1168":"okolo 1168","Touraine, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France":"Indre-et-Loire, Centre, Francie","Kempsford, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Kempsford, Gloucestershire, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"about 1123–about 1168":"omkring 1123–omkring 1168","1131–1187":"1131–1187","1157–1187":"1157–1187","1123–1168":"1123–1168","1168":"1168","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","about 1123":"omkring 1123","about 1157":"omkring 1157","about 1168":"omkring 1168","Touraine, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France":"Indre-et-Loire, Centre, Frankrig","Kempsford, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Kempsford, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"about 1123–about 1168":"circa 1123–circa 1168","1131–1187":"1131–1187","1157–1187":"1157–1187","1123–1168":"1123–1168","1168":"1168","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","about 1123":"circa 1123","about 1157":"circa 1157","about 1168":"circa 1168","Touraine, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France":"Indre-et-Loire, Centre, Frankrijk","Kempsford, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Kempsford, Gloucestershire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1123–about 1168":"about 1123–about 1168","1131–1187":"1131–1187","1157–1187":"1157–1187","1123–1168":"1123–1168","1168":"1168","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","about 1123":"about 1123","about 1157":"about 1157","about 1168":"about 1168","Touraine, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France":"Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France","Kempsford, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Kempsford, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Payne","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i> (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>), a fairly common personal name among Normans. It derived from a word that originally meant ‘villager, rustic’, later ‘heathen’, but it had doubtless lost these connotations in its use as a late medieval personal name. This name has also been established in Ireland since the 14th century.","History: Thomas Payne, who was a freeman of Plymouth Colony in 1639, was the founder of a large American family, which included Robert Treat Paine (1731–1814), one of the signers of the Declaration of Independence. See also   Paine  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Payn","meanings":["English (Kent): variant of   Payne  ."]},{"name":"Payen","meanings":["French: from the Old French personal name <i>Pagen</i>, <i>Paien</i>, from Latin <i>Paganus</i>, from <i>paganus</i> ‘country-dweller’, a derivative of <i>pagus</i> ‘of or relating to the countryside’, possibly given to a child not yet baptized (because of its later sense of ‘pagan, heathen’). Alternatively, a nickname for a country-born person. This surname is also found in the West Indies (mainly Haiti) and Mauritius.","English: variant of   Payne  ."]},{"name":"Pagan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Jose, Luis, Juan, Angel, Carlos, Rafael, Ramon, Pedro, Francisco, Jesus, Miguel, Julio.","Spanish and Catalan: Castilianized form (<b>Pagán</b>) of Catalan <b>Pagà</b>, from the Late Latin personal name <i>Paganus</i>, which as a derivative of Latin <i>pagus</i> ‘outlying village’ originally meant ‘villager’ (see   Payne  ). Alternatively, in some cases, a topographic name from Catalan <i>pagà</i> ‘heath’ (from the same Latin word <i>pagus</i>).","English: from the Middle English and Old French personal name <i>Pai(e)n</i>, <i>Pagen</i>, from Late Latin <i>Paganus</i> (see   Payne  , compare 1 above)."]},{"name":"Paynes","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Paine","meanings":["English: variant of   Payne  .","History: The author of the republican treatise <i>The Rights of Man</i>, Thomas Paine (1737–1809), left England for North America in the mid 1770s, where he became involved in the movement that led to independence. His pamphlet of 1776, <i>Common Sense</i>, influenced the Declaration of Independence and furnished some of the arguments justifying it."]},{"name":"Pank","meanings":["English (Norfolk): perhaps from an unrecorded Middle English personal name <i>Pank(e)</i>. It could be a shortened form of <i>Pancok</i>, which is probably a pet form of <i>Pane</i> (see   Payne  ).","Sorbian: nickname from a diminutive of <i>pan</i> ‘mister, lord, landlord’ (see   Pan  ). Compare   Panke  ."]},{"name":"Pane","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Angelo, Antonio, Salvatore, Aldo, Carmela, Carmine, Ciro, Concetta, Enzo, Giuseppe, Mario, Armando, Claudio, Macario, Remigio.","Italian: from <i>pane</i> ‘bread’, used as a metonymic occupational name for a baker or as a nickname meaning ‘good thing’, and also as a personal name. This surname is also found in southern France and Corsica.","English: variant of   Payne  ."]},{"name":"Panes","meanings":["English (Somerset): variant of   Payne  , with genitival or post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Pannell","meanings":["English (southeastern):","possibly from Middle English <i>panel</i>, <i>panel(l)e</i> ‘cloth, saddle-cloth, saddle’ or ‘pane (of glass)’, hence a metonymic occupational name for a maker of such items.","from the Middle English personal name <i>Paynel</i> (Old French <i>Payenel</i>, Latin <i>Paganellus</i>), a pet form of   Payne   (from Latin <i>Paganus</i>)."]},{"name":"Penson","meanings":["English:","patronymic from the Middle English female personal name <i>Penn</i>, a pet form of <i>Pernel</i>, or perhaps from the Middle English personal name   Payne   + <i>-son</i>. See   Penn  ,   Parnell  .","habitational name from Penson in North Huish (Devon), which derives from the Anglo-Norman French personal name <i>Payn(e)</i> (see   Payne  ) + Middle English <i>toun</i> ‘village, town, settlement’ (Old English <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’)."]}]},{"name":"De","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Payne De Kempsford was born about 1123, in Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France. He had at least 1 daughter with Weruga de Morre. He died about 1168, in Kempsford, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 47."},"et":{"about 1123–about 1168":"umbes 1123–umbes 1168","1131–1187":"1131–1187","1157–1187":"1157–1187","1123–1168":"1123–1168","1168":"1168","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","about 1123":"umbes 1123","about 1157":"umbes 1157","about 1168":"umbes 1168","Touraine, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France":"Indre-et-Loire, Centre, Prantsusmaa","Kempsford, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Kempsford, Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1123–about 1168":"noin 1123–noin 1168","1131–1187":"1131–1187","1157–1187":"1157–1187","1123–1168":"1123–1168","1168":"1168","1157":"1157","1123":"1123","1187":"1187","1131":"1131","about 1123":"noin 1123","about 1157":"noin 1157","about 1168":"noin 1168","Touraine, Indre-et-Loire, Centre, France":"Indre-et-Loire, Centre, Ranska","Kempsford, Gloucestershire, England, United King